### Importing a catalog
This feature allows to import a source file to be used as a catalog in a Data Transformation project.

The functionality is useful, for example, when you want to import a catalog that was previously defined by the customer and modify some values.

> Note

It is always possible to modify the imported data structure.

> Warning

This action will permanently delete and overwrite the existing data structure.

- Open the XML Reader resource in the configuration editor as described in [Configuring DT3 Project Resources.](/doxee-platform/docs/configuring-dt3-project-resources)

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Import catalog**). The guided configuration panel is displayed:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Configure the required parameters:

**Section**

**Field**

**Description**

**FILE TYPE**

**Select type**

Select the required option to interpret the source file:

**Fixed width **

- **Delimited**

> Note

After reading the imported source file, the system preserves the properties of the columns defined by the user also in output.

**Delimiters**

Select the separator character used in the imported source file. The available options are:

- **Semicolon **

- **Space**

- **User defined **

- **Tab**

- **Comma**

**Text qualifier**

Select the qualifier character that you want to use to identify text fields. The available options are:

- **None**

- **Double apostrophes ('') **

- **Single apostrophe (')**

**ENCODING**

Select the type of character encoding that you want to use to interpret the source file. The available options are:

- **Ascii**

- **ISO-8859-1 **

- **ISO-8859-15 **

- **UTF-8**

- **UTF-16BE **

- **UTF-16LE **

- **UCS-2**

- **Windows 1250 (Central Europe)**

- **Windows 1251 ( Cyrillic)**

- **Windows 1252 (Western Europe)**

- **Windows 1253 (Greek)**

- **Windows 1254 (Turkish)**

- **Windows 1255 (Hebrew)**

- **Windows 1256 (Arabic)**

- **Windows 1257 (Baltic)**

- **Windows 1258 (Vietnamese) **

- **EBCDIC Cp1140**

- **EBCDIC Cp1144**

**VALID DATA START LINE**

Indicate which line of the source file to use to define the type of data in the column by entering its numeric value.

- Click **Continue**. The second part of the guided configuration panel is displayed:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- In the **Input method **section, configure the required parameters:

*(optional) *Select the option **First line contains fields definition **to indicate that the system should use the first line of the source file to define the type of data in the column.

> Note

This option is selected by default.

Selecting this option enables the **Append to existing data **option (see below).

- Select the required input method. The available options are:

**Option**

**Description**

**Import data from source**

Import the selected source file and load it into the project, making it editable.

> Note

If you enabled the **First line contains fields definition **option:

Select the **Append to existing data **option to add the imported source file data to the existing catalog.

or

- Deselect the **Append to existing data **option to delete all data from the catalog and replace it with the imported source file data.Your content goes here

**Import source inside project**

Import the selected source file and load it into the project, without making it editable.

**Read data from source at runtime**

Import the selected source file without loading it into the project, making it available as read-only in the output file generation phase.

- Drag &amp; drop the catalog file to import into the highlighted area, or click **browse **to select if from your local filesystem.

> Important

The source file to be imported must be a text file in record format, for example a CSV file.

The system does not support binary files, such as XLS or MDB files, or XML files.

- Click **Continue **to confirm and close the window. The working area displays the imported catalog, based on the properties selected by the user; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Validating a catalog
This feature allows you to validate a catalog and verify that there are no duplicate values in the key column.

This functionality is useful, for example, when a key column contains a large number of values and you want to quickly verify that there are no duplicate values.

- Open the Catalog resource in the configuration editor as described in [Configuring DT3 Project Resources](/doxee-platform/docs/configuring-dt3-project-resources).

> Note

Make sure that at least one key column has been defined in the catalog.

- Click ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Validate catalog**). A notification message informs you if the operation was completed successfully or ended with errors; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Tip

Click on the **Details **link in the notification message to view more details in the [DT3 Message Console](/doxee-platform/docs/dt3-message-console).

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Configuring the Catalog's general settings
The **Settings **panel allows to edit the name of the catalog and to add a description, and to view the reading and interpretation properties of the imported catalog.

- Open the Catalog resource in the configuration editor as described in [Configuring DT3 Project Resources](/doxee-platform/docs/configuring-dt3-project-resources).

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Settings**). The **Settings **panel is displayed on the right; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Configure the required parameters:

**Section**

**Parameter**

**Description**

**General**

**Name**

Name of the Catalog

**Description**

*(optional) *Brief description of the Catalog

**Import options**

**File type**

Source file type, based on the previously defined fields in the current project. The possible values are:

**Fixed width **

- **Delimited**

> Note

This field is not editable.

**Delimiters**

Separator character used in the imported source file. The possible values are:

- **Semicolon **

- **Space**

- **User defined **

- **Tab**

- **Comma**

> Note

This field is not editable.

**Text qualifier**

Qualifier character used to identify text fields. The possible values are:

- **None**

- **Double apostrophes ('') **

- **Single apostrophe (')**

> Note

This field is not editable.

**Encoding**

Character encoding used to interpret the source file. The possible values are:

- **Ascii**

- **ISO-8859-1 **

- **ISO-8859-15 **

- **UTF-8**

- **UTF-16BE **

- **UTF-16LE **

- **UCS-2**

- **Windows 1250 (Central Europe)**

- **Windows 1251 (Cyrillic)**

- **Windows 1252 (Western Europe)**

- **Windows 1253 (Greek)**

- **Windows 1254 (Turkish)**

- **Windows 1255 (Hebrew)**

- **Windows 1256 (Arabic)**

- **Windows 1257 (Baltic)**

- **Windows 1258 (Vietnamese) **

- **EBCDIC Cp1140**

- **EBCDIC Cp1144**

> Note

This field is not editable.

**Valid data start line**

Line of the source used to define the type of data in the column.
